Parliament did not support an amendment to free Tymoshenko
Ukraine’s parliament has today rejected the proposal to repeal the amendment to the section of the Criminal Code condemning opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the door to the ex-prison of the former prime minister, but parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce the penalties for economic crimes in the second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison by the alleged signing of a deal with Russia disadvantageous to Ukraine on the purchase of natural gas.
The ruling is not yet firm, the appeals court has an obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that this was a political revenge of the regime, and even in the West there have been doubts about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to remove paragraph 365 of the Criminal Code, which condemned the former prime minister, was supported by 147 deputies in the vote.
226 votes were required for approval.
