Daily menu of an obese child: not breakfast and dinner wrapped
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 have overweight problems, where overweight affects 9% of the school population and obesity at 5%.
Obese children mostly come from families with an unhealthy lifestyle, as evidenced by current research.
It again demonstrates the importance of the environment where it grows for the healthy development of the person, as well as the models that serve as a reference.
At the table, obese children feed, for example, on stools at least twice as often as children in normal weight families.
For dinner, more than 19% of the obese had eaten fries the day before the analysis, which is linked to the prevention program “Obesity is not a coincidence.”
In families of overweight children there is no practice of sports, which is applicable to most families today, where only 15% of children responded that their parents, at least once a week, find time for exercise.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last school year and nearly 900 Basic Education children from all over the Czech Republic participated in it.
It was already the second edition of the program "Obesity is not a coincidence", which supports the General Health Insurance Company and the Unilever company.
So far, more than 12,000 children have participated in the project from the 4th to the 8th year.
A proper diet and plenty of family exercise are determining factors, which make the number of overweight and even obese children significantly decrease.
“Only half of the children surveyed have responded that they have five daily meals according to the diet: breakfast, lunch, lunch, snack and dinner, which is one of the basic conditions for a healthy diet,” one of the survey results says.
No breakfast but with built-in for dinner
Experts warn that, in healthy development, the details, which also count, are important, such as having a fixed time for breakfast in the family.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23% of school-age families have breakfast at the same time.
In most families, everyone has breakfast alone.
But the worst part was finding that 10% of households don’t have breakfast at all.
Breakfast is, however, the basis of a correct daily diet.
The study shows that in the families of obese children, insane potato chips are consumed much more often.
Almost everyone – regardless of weight – drinks sweet refreshments daily (70%).
As a rule, more than 40% of the children surveyed do sports, however, among their parents this result is reduced to less than half, only 15%.
Make your diet
The next phase of the study made it possible for the chosen boys (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own diets from all possible offers according to their tastes and opinions.
"The dietary preferences of Czech children aged between 12 and 15 years, from the point of view of a healthy diet, are far from ideal."
Among his favorite foods are pasta, meat and sweets.
“The popularity of sweet soft drinks is alarming in particular,” the study’s final report warns.
As a main meal, the pasta is taken from the palm and followed closely by the poultry meat.
Practically, children always reject legumes and the taste for fish and vegetables is very low.
Change to Healthy Habits
At the same time, the study shows that children are willing to change their eating habits if they receive the right information.
“In the control group of the study participants, who filled out the questionnaire after finishing the prevention program “Obesity is not a coincidence,” a significant change was made in many cases in favor of the principles of a healthy diet,” the study notes.
Attention is drawn, for example, to sweet refreshments, where many children would start to prefer normal and running water.
Children would also more often choose poultry and fish in the questionnaire for the main meal and restrict the consumption of sweet food and flour derivatives.
