In Need for Speed: The Run, we compete across America.
Reviewer
A trip, in principle unconcerned, gets complicated because of a series of improper neglects of a routine trip during the morning shift.
To a certain extent, expectations were met, but this was of no use, if, in fact, nothing extraordinary was meant to be done.
The new release, to which The Run is added to the title, sparked great expectations even before its release.
It promised that it would give new airs to the old racing saga Need for Speed and, as a result, it appears as a game that should not end up being a genre of action again without more.
We are also curious to know how the scenes would be inserted, where the main character descends from the car and walks on his own foot.
As is usually the case in the NFS series, the results don’t vary much from what we expected.
There are races that can be given as acceptable, but in the total count points are lost due to absurd failures, which have already appeared in the series for years.
In reality, mistakes cannot be called, but rather the incomprehensible devastation of programmers.
The adventure begins very well.
He introduces you to a story whose protagonist, Jack, has certain personal problems; to solve them, he is offered to participate in an illegal race across America.
You sit on the wheel on the west coast, in San Francisco, and your mission is to get to New York first.
The idea is to offer something interesting.
The route is divided into ten stages and then more than fifty races.
From this it is deduced that each race takes place on a different route and the stages are located in different environments, which are quite diverse and interesting.
Thus, one does not even remotely have the feeling that the game always offers the same.
Some of the environments are even pleasing to the eye, although the technical level of the chart is equivalent to that of previous series deliveries.
Therefore, it is nothing from the other world.
But the walk through the desert, the autumn landscape or the high mountains covered with snow produce a very pleasant visual effect.
In addition, races are diversified from time to time by an atypical element.
Thus, for example, in the desert you will find a sandstorm that decreases visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains you have to be careful not to bury an avalanche.
According to that, each of the races is very well developed.
There are only a couple of models, but that’s enough.
For a while, you try to advance a required amount of rivals (normally in a classic race), then try to earn time (classical timed duel) and then expect a duel against a single opponent.
In the midst of all this, sometimes the police appear, which only makes things even more difficult.
The novelty is the landscapes outside the car.
Interactive animations are presented when Jack, in most cases, has to escape from someone and you have to help him, always pressing the right button at the right time.
Nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are far fewer landscapes in the game than one would expect (in particular, there are only three).
But the end result is positive, because this element does not become annoying and, in the context already mentioned, it is one of the elements that make the game more interesting.
The driving model follows the tracks of previous episodes.
That means it’s not a big deal anymore, but it can’t be said to be bad.
If you are looking for a realistic simulation, you can already look elsewhere.
But a race conceived with enough action suits quite well this style of driving, although we can find something better between the games of the competition.
So far, everything's in order.
But problems arise after a while.
Unlike the correct driving patterns, the same is no longer the case with collisions.
From games of this type you can’t expect to recreate complicated deformations and collisions, but in fact before a hit against any object, you can’t predict how your car will react, so not everything is in order.
It is typical that when you make a very tight forward or circle the car with normal traffic, there are only slight rocks, but in other almost identical situations, your car ends up making unchecked pirouettes.
It even ends up completely destroyed.
Thanks to the reset system, no major problems arise, but it can put you in a bad mood.
The resets are programmed in such a way that when you suffer an accident or get off the track, the game returns you to the last rescue point on the track.
However, in each race there are only five resets available.
If you consume them all, you have to restart the race from the beginning.
So it’s just a help in case something goes wrong, but it’s not very reliable.
Sometimes, even the reset doesn’t help, it just helps to learn the given stage of memory.
A big disadvantage of the game is that the same facts are repeated in different places.
In some curves, for example, it is necessary to enter in a specific way; otherwise, they are impossible to take.
Other times you will find "civil" vehicles at some point always with the same configuration, even if you are the first, fifth or you arrive five minutes before or after.
This makes you angry especially in situations, when you see that two cars that go to the meeting in opposite directions, your opponent forwards without problems, but when you arrive, you must turn or brake.
It’s the same when you arrive, because it’s programmed because the “surprise” will always happen in front of your nose.
Opponents also have one more advantage.
Throughout the match you will arrive at places where, regardless of the moment, the same opponent will always advance in the same place.
In addition, this happens at the end of the game, on a long bridge, which is even more shocking.
Your opponent must arrive before you, at any price.
When it goes in front of you, it makes it difficult for you to see the cars coming in front, so at first you can make the car a mess.
You can understand the idea of creating a game with maximum doses of suspense and adrenaline, but the execution is so apparent that it will surely disappoint you right away.
And it’s a shame, because even though the travel model is simple, the game is fun and action-packed, so it’s often not possible to follow in detail what happens or where.
And it really doesn’t matter, if the merit takes the idea with fifty exclusive tracks or the qualifying in the race so that it doesn’t break the boredom, or anything else.
An unusual idea is to change cars during races.
You have to pay attention to the gas suppliers next to the road, because right there you have to change the car, although in the vast majority of cases it will be enough for you to have what you have.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, strong American cars for straight highways and exotic super sports cars for technical driving, for example, by curved mountain roads.
In addition, the main narrative thread also appears a parallel challenge thread, i.e. there are races in specific places that you will know by the stories.
Here you will get not only medals, but also experience points for your profile, which serves both for the challenges and the stories.
Upon reaching the top level, the driver opens up several possibilities, starting with the car and ending with funds for the profile.
At the same time, an online Autolog feature is connected, which compares your results with those of other players and makes available other community functions.
One of the most difficult elements to understand is how the last race in history is made.
By car you arrive to the subway tunnel (pass), where you get to run in the dark through the tracks (pass).
The speedometer marks you between 150 and 200 km/h (pass) and, suddenly, behind you the convoy of the metro arrives and takes you forward without further ado.
In the editorial board we will surely have a discussion about this for several days, about whether during the programming of the game no one thought even a little or whether the real authors take us for a bunch of fools.
The technical part of the game is nothing extraordinary, but at least the overall visual effects result in most pleasant cases, sometimes even superb.
What a pity that, in the most tense moments, the image quality is reduced and, sometimes, in a serious way.
This especially affects accidents where many participants are involved, when the continuous image quality is no longer valid.
The audio is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In order to please most of the youth group, the soundtrack belongs to the category "each of his father and his mother", but it can be assumed that no one would buy the game just for his music.
The final feeling of Need for Speed: The Run is quite confusing.
If the game avoids absolutely silly mistakes, we would have trouble claiming that The Run is the best NFS game of recent years.
It gives the feeling that the game is not over.
The fun is assured, but be prepared because mistakes will hit you in the eye with the force of airport reflectors.
