Brand story:
The innovative IBM begins its second century of existence
If someone were to look for a term that would very accurately define IBM’s strategy, the most approximate would be “long-term.”
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that perceives itself as current and yet it has been a hundred years since its founding.
The basis of this long-range character was laid by the first head of the firm, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He already coined the motto that many problems in the world have a solution if people are willing to think.
Its motto "Think!" became its seal, around which the life of the giant future will be built (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
Watson was also the basis of a carefully raised corporate culture.
“For us, IBM involves long-term thinking, a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM has survived and thrived for a hundred years for that reason, because it remained true to its basic principles, but without fear of the changes around it.
That has allowed us, during our first century, to transform technology, business and society.
We hope to thrive even more in our second century,” said Samuel J. Palmisano, the current director of the company.
A sophisticated system
Watson, already in the 1930s, was concerned about the care of his employees as the Bata entrepreneur in the Czech Republic (the IBM employees were among the first American operators to enjoy paid vacations, insurance, stylish uniforms and a sophisticated pay system that rewarded the best inventors and sellers.
The same long-term sophistication is maintained by IBM in its relationship with the customer.
From the very beginning the company knew how to discover talent (being one of the first companies in the world to end any kind of discrimination, it could choose without problems).
In line with the anti-discrimination strategy is IBM’s current plan, whereby Palmisano will replace him next year with a woman: Virginia Rometty.
She has been working at IBM for thirty years, where she has been head of sales, marketing and strategy.
In recent years, IBM has participated in so-called virtual meetings, rain of ideas online, from which countless future strategies and innovations arise.
It is not surprising that ideas arise, as almost half a million people work in the firm.
An institution with a good reputation
The fixed position in the business provides the company with a strong internal and external image.
“From the beginning, IBM maintained an institution concept rather than a technology company,” says Harvard Business School economist and author of the book about IBM Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
“IBM is not a technology company, but a company that tries to solve business problems for technology users,” says George Colony of Forrester Research.
As the company itself says there is a difference between entering the business and directly creating a business.
IBM – or the “Green Great” – as it is known in the U.S. familiarly because of its logo, has become in the last hundred years one of the largest companies in the world.
It is possibly the most versatile technology company (develops both equipment and programs, infrastructure and web hosting services within a wide range of services, ranging from servers to nanotechnology).
It holds the largest number of patents from all U.S. technology companies and five of its employees have been awarded the Nobel Prize.
His inventions include ATMs, payment cards, financial exchanges, barcodes, and floppy disks.
IBM is expected to make $220 billion this year, making it the second-largest technology company by market capitalization (the first being Apple), when it surpassed Microsoft for the first time in 1996.
Looking to the future
Not all products and innovations have just satisfied the taste of customers and the moment (IBM did not bet for its own operating system, OS/2, Prodigy online services or IBM PCjr computers).
“If your business is based on moving forward, it cannot be emotionally anchored in the past,” said Samuel J. Palmisano.
That’s why IBM has no problem building its bases on other platforms (and also, if they don’t work, abandons them).
And that’s the difference from the competition, Microsoft, which basically stays and always falls exclusively with Windows.
Technology of the Future
In terms of sales, IBM is primarily dedicated to services, of which approximately one-fifth are programs and another-fifth are equipment.
However, even in 1990 the teams accounted for more than half of the supplier’s share.
As of 2000, IBM has sold low-performing assets worth a total of $15 billion. During the same period, it has invested $58 billion in the purchase of future technology.
Investments have continued since 2008, when the modern world financial crisis first manifested itself.
IBM is acting on the premise of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who during the great economic crisis of 29 increased investments.
It seems that so far the IBM company has managed to cope with the crisis.
The value of IBM’s shares since the beginning of 2008 has grown strategically up to 120%, the company’s net profit has not stopped increasing.
IBM’s currency is to change everything except its value.
We can therefore expect that when the next crisis comes, this flexible giant will endure.
IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Flight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York City a hundred years ago, its original name being Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted as early as 1924 – originally a brand used in the Canadian and South American branches.
The foundation that gave rise to the birth of IBM stems from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
It had inventions such as the famous "check-in clock", which allows to control the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also presided over his Supervisory Board.
Flint signed the head of a competition company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him with the management of the company.
The new leader eclipsed the founder of IBM (Watson’s ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are based).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business appliances, from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years that Watson ran the company, turnover doubled by $9 million and the company’s large expansion began across the continents.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, almost forty years after occupying the boss’s chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
In 1964, IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "fish", which established the computer standard of the time, came to the market under the name IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, in turn, acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began offering comprehensive, high value-added advice and services.
The strategy that IBM has paid for the past three years is the Smarter Planet concept, that is, “a smarter planet.”
Its objective is to make a more rational use of technology, although areas have not yet been planned or circumstances improved, for example in relation to transport and city administration.
For the commerce sector, IBM recently introduced the “Smart Commerce” platform that allows retailers to manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
Already in 1932 it opened a branch in Czechoslovakia, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, the IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is in Prague. Also here is a world-renowned research team working with voice recognition.
