How Travel Prices Have Evolved Since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time were mostly selling trips only to the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists went on holiday to the beaches of the RDA (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when one could travel to Yugoslavia, however, then the Yugoslav regime leaned west and the trips of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e., also the Czechoslovak ones) were not allowed to travel freely and individually not even by the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, the individual trip was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West at the time, but one had to queue up with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night like that, or have “well-knowns” at the agency.
Still, not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" that was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", which thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without exchange guarantee, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there was a large number of cottages and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired.
The Czech way of travel has been a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was no longer going to spend the holidays in the RDA or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware, the fact that to the present favorite destination, Croatia, until 1989, you could not travel freely, because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
In the early 1990s visa exemptions were imposed to travel to the neighbouring states of Western Europe, resulting in a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, did not see themselves fed up with excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, groups of Czechs slept in parks in tents, as our income at the time did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was taking food (contains, sausages, etc.) with them to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the Czech crown convertibility, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living increased and with it also average wages, which around 1997 led to an increase in travel demand.
As the demand for travel increased, from 1997 on a regular basis, the agencies began to prepare travel using charter flights, which led to an incredible decrease in travel prices compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for the volume of passengers.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs were already traveling visa-free to almost all developed countries except the US, which further simplified our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism occurred as early as 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, every year direct charter flights with Czech tourists depart to distant and warm countries. This winter will be flown directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries currently visit them about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, arrived in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. removed visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, have spent more than 15,000 Czech crowns per head on trips abroad, including on-site expenses.
