Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Are Studying You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of the far-right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was simply another type that aired his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to having carried out a massacre in Norway in July, which left 77 dead, faced his first public hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of his time ahead of his attack on his computer, talking to some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social networks.
After this summer’s tragedy, the researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - you just have to log in to Facebook.
“We realized that it wasn’t that hard to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European digital populism by the British study center DEMOS.
Facebook’s personal information suite is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic characteristics with scientific accuracy – the way sellers have been using it for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans from right-wing groups across Europe and then directed ads to them, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey asking about their educational level, attitudes towards violence, and optimism about their own future.
Upon arriving via Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers from 14 far-right matches in 11 European countries – all without leaving the office.
“It’s a totally new way to do an investigation,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, men and angry about immigration.
However, in a kind of twist, “those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind the computer screen.”
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers, and political scientists are using the site to study everything from health problems to social trends as expressed in “Likes,” messages on walls, and state updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook’s “supernova of data” is generating a surge in research, driving the number of academic jobs with the site’s name in the title to nearly 800 percent in the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn’t approach with a folder on the street.
“Before, when you were trying to survey people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.”
“You would have to go through the game, and they would never allow you access,” Bartlett says.
"Facebook removes all that - you go to them directly."
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social issues.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues found that college students who talked about their drink feats on Facebook had a significantly higher risk of having drinking problems than students who remained silent on the topic.
Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as residential counselors, could control the site and intervene to help a student publish too many state updates with their drinkers.
“You can’t treat a problem if you can’t diagnose it,” said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children’s Research Institute.
“We have found a way to identify children at risk who would otherwise not be diagnosed.”
Facebook is also constantly “clicking” on its own population to get data.
The site’s Data Team has compiled statistics on the status of the relationship and Valentine’s Day, the expectation of electoral participation in the mid-2010 legislative period, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using the information that can be accessed - research data from the site should be long overdue.
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching, like it or not – the sacrifice of being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is to allow the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect your data offline, online is a free bar for everyone.
“I don’t think many of the users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be examining their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at London’s Knowledge Lab, about a 2006 study that carried out with students’ public Facebook walls.
"As far as they were concerned, it was only between them and their friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research topic is being completely honest.
On Facebook, it’s impossible to know that some of the user’s profile information and wall messages are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn says.
That’s why, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn believes that a subjectpaper and a pen are still the best research tools that no one can use.
“There is no substitute for going into the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
“Social research is supposed to be about social – and a lot of social still happens offline.”
