7 Lessons from Steve Jobs’ Lost Interview, Shown in a Theater This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs, on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford – distinguishing the genius of technology as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most revealing, in a recently rediscovered Jobs interview that has been unearthed as the lead in a series of special screenings in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about the business processes and product workflows.
He was undoubtedly a self-recognised designer, dreamer, and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a yonki of flowcharts – a man who believed many executives suffered from “a disease that consists in thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product.”
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds about the dawn of the personal computer, and sat for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At that time it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working intensively at his new computer company NeXT, waiting for popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringely's interview was used in Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during their transportation.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full VHS copy was discovered in the director's garage.
This slightly reissued archive material is the basis of Steve Jobs: The 68-minute lost interview that arrives at the Landmark cinemas this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there is great silence between the questions and the answers - from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, looking for accuracy.
There are also times when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient because of Cringely’s questions, pushing him to go faster toward the most important topics or arguments.
Filmed before the Pixar era, the iPod or iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic in The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what other companies see as doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
One thing is to read posthumous evaluations of Jobs’ career, but there is something raw and inspiring about Jobs that we see here, the anxious dreamer on the verge of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, he went and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences of The Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
“Throughout the years in business, I’ve always asked, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers that give you invariably are, ‘Oh, that’s just the way it’s done.’
No one knows why he does what he does, in business no one thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs takes his efforts to simplify Apple’s accounting in detail.
Disappointing by the way in which the costs were recorded – often starting with a “standard cost” that was made to the eye of good cover, and then adjusted to a “variable” – he developed an automated factory that ensured that they could determine the commercial costs in detail.
The joke to the Pope:
Jobs narrates the "Blue Box" he built himself with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
It has been widely written about the device, but Jobs’ euphoria here when describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public telephone, making one call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
“We were wrapping things around the world a half dozen times and you shouted through the public phone and came back a minute later to the public phone next door,” Jobs says with a laugh.
“We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
We both didn’t know much, but we could build a little thing that could control a giant thing – it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think there would ever have been Apple without it.
Jobs continues to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandon, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and asking to speak with the Pope while doing his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two burst into turmoil just before the Pope himself was awakened to go and answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling by phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call.
Shortly after his 20-minute telephone conversation, Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and shaped my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees.”
Jobs later became one of HP’s employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a small cathode tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste time with that machine and write programs for it.
On improvising innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the go.
Soon in his career, as he devoted himself to selling a handful of baseplates, he asked a customer if he could assemble the whole equipment.
Working with just 30 days of credit, I had to figure out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalls the struggles he faced in the development of a computer mouse:
“I remember having dramatic arguments ... they were screaming at me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got bored and went out and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
About big companies losing strength:
Long before he led the revival of Apple, Jobs propheticly predicted how many industry leaders would stumble upon his vision, and lose control of his market share.
“Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better photocopiers and printers, and what?”
You have the monopoly of market share, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is this kind of people who end up running companies and the people in charge of the products are expelled from the forum for decision-making.
The genius of the products that led to that monopoly position is blamed on people who do not have the notion of good products vs. bad products - knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took the victory's defeat.
About innovation as an artistic expression:
“There’s a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, it changes and it grows.”
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make – some things you can’t make electrons do, glass does them, robots do them, factories do them.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain — these concepts — adjust them all at once...
In the end, it all boils down to taste – it boils down to trying to expose yourself to the best a human team has done, and then trying to adapt those things to which you are doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We've never had a shame about stealing great ideas.
What made the Macintosh great in part was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who casually were the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn’t for computer science, it could be doing wonderful things in other fields.
