And, again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about traps in school and university examinations are very widespread.
There have been cases in which teachers have given the answers to the exams to the students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we find ourselves?
On any given day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That’s for sure, many of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that the unknowns lied three times in the first 10 minutes of getting to know each other.
Detecting lies, or “the location of lies,” is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: “I have you,” the detection of deception is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about the lie have been rebuffed.
The liars look into the eyes.
They don’t always sneeze, sneeze, or sneeze.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, question formation, and times.
I spent several years researching scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world—especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or negotiating management.
Good liars have the ability to read well to others, making them feel good, managing their own emotions and feeling intuitively how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "self-directed lies", while women say more "self-directed" lies -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people are less likely to lie to their partners than to tell their non-married people (to tell them that they are not married).
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do I know if someone is lying?
First, observe the usual behavior of the subject.
This is called “creating a baseline.”
It helps to provide reference points to then measure the changes.
Observe the subject’s posture, laughter, and vocal characteristics.
It’s best to know if someone normally hits you with their foot all the time so you don’t make unfair accusations when you see your feet hitting you in the middle of the meeting.
Next, look for misleading, verbal, and non-verbal behavioral groups.
Consider these behavioural groups as alarm signals, not as evidence of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the top of their body by trying to remember their story, they can point their feet at the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or display a “post-interview disapproval”—that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all difficult questions have ended.
Questioners often falsely show that the interview has ended only to seek that post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the subject’s vocabulary.
Scott Peterson put his leg to the bottom and used the past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
People who cheat can also use a distancer language: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... to what I am... to understand."
This makes the response a perception rather than a fact and is often an alert signal.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
