The appointed Italian prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet on Wednesday with the president of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and has put the entire eurozone at risk.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
It is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not clear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he would present the president with the result of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
“I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country’s ability to overcome this difficult phase,” the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not say explicitly that he could form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
The “framework is now well-defined,” he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than normal, as Italy fights a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the beaten-up confidence in Italy.
Underscoring the pressure on Monti to hurry, market instability put the yield of Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be rescued.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian boss Confindustria, told the press after meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government a lot."
We believe that this Government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti’s chances of success were driven considerably by the support of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, whom the crisis forced him to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy’s largest party, is significant because so far many of its members have opposed the technocrat majority government that is forming Monti.
Parliamentary Support
