At its conference A technological opinion of the Baches, given in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, it was announced that the laboratory at its disposal develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical strength, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve its performance and therefore the formation of streams.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of high molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the floor its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt is that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrade it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
The above means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but it is being modified during the day according to the environmental and temperature conditions, warned the specialist in chemical engineering.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt carpet, consisting of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that make up the folder, he pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
By transiting the vehicles and generating effort, it allows forces to spread very well on the floor.
If it were modified asphalt they would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphalt carpet, it abounds, a last layer is placed called the rolling carpet, which is made of a fine stone material, i.e. a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As it is the layer that will be in contact with the tires of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the road.
Being the part of the floor that will receive and disseminate the efforts, the treading folder also requires having the appropriate thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken care.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt carpet.
When the ground becomes wet, the water diffuses into the interior of the folder and it is difficult to get out, this causes a softening of all layers of the floor and, therefore, the formation of bumps.
In the process of forming a tray, he said, the first to wear is the bearing film and only then the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantaneously, but it is a process that should be attended to the first signs with appropriate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that vehicular load is another important factor in the formation of bumps and therefore the thickness of each layer of the floor must always go in relation to the vehicular load and ensure that it is met, to prevent frequent bumps from forming.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already even on the market and allow to repair the slag easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
