It is appropriate that an election meeting be the time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it studies the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic evolution will double the electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge part of the world’s population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, it will be necessary to alleviate the growing scarcity of fossil resources to continue producing electricity continuously, not forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, a topic that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear energy.
This is not the case either in Belgium, which submits its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, or in Switzerland, which only aims to build state-of-the-art power plants.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few examples, continue with determination with their projects.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of a interrupted power plant after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality goes against such a speech.
Berlin’s election will lead to an increase in the price of electricity, an increased energy dependence on the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noticed.
It is necessary to meditate on the case of Denmark.
Europe’s champion in the wind sector, of which it gets 30% of its electricity, is also one of the big users of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbors pay an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from Europe’s cheapest electricity.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would represent a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would remain realistic of the wonderful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not show opposition in principle to that type of energy, according to the polls.
Recall that the energy policy of our country has lost building an industrial sector with 125,000 director jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it spans a galaxy of SMEs specializing in international markets that can create non-localizable jobs.
If France decides to abandon nuclear energy, it would be the sacrifice of much of those SMEs and the loss of the 6 billion euros annually in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would commission an EPR designed to run for sixty years, when its manufacturer is expected to collapse?
To solve the nuclear energy equation, one must admit that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no diabolical source.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear power, it is essential to maintain the highest level of security.
In France, we have a Security Authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both existing power plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, that of Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it caused no consequences for either people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and some unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two natural disasters of an unprecedented magnitude, which resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as did the previous two.
Thanks to these advances and cooperation between the security authorities, and French and German operators and builders, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
As all the electrical actors who want to build a power plant study it, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for Areva and EDF competitors, as it would leave them free to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is essential and legitimate to look for the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotions, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy applied by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of France’s “country of human rights”.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has jumped the headlines, with the Interior Minister (see the May 23 Liberation newspaper) declaring from the past that France “does not need foreign talents, workers or waiters.”
However, it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
The point is that, on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the orientation by stating in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has about two million immigrant workers", while on the left, the tone was set by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take charge of all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of the national territory by a crowd of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are considered a burden to the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In its programme, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Hollande is limited to including banalities, indicating that co-development will solve the “migration problem”.
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be profitable electorally, but economically it comes out very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent paper summarizing the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus on the impact on migration among the stakeholders.
The restriction of immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, particularly low-skilled workers, by pressing for their wages to be reduced.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are rather complementary than substitutes for national workers and are mainly employed in sectors with no employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country that lacks anesthetists, complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to have a positive impact on the salaries and employment of nationals.
Taking into account the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migratory flows represents an increase in real long-term wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, not to mention the fact that the diversity that immigrants contribute contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel prizes and companies like Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, as they contribute an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization calculates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who reaches the age of 30 will make a net contribution (less expenditures) of 150,000 euros to the average public budgets throughout his life.
At the beginning of his tenure, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go looking for the growth points that he lacked "with his teeth".
Those teeth, which dissipated immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it only needs to think about a European democracy
Democracy is a precious good, but also a fragile one.
The European continent should be able to remember this because, although it was invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, throughout the 20th century it has suffered the tragedies of the World War, totalitarianisms, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that, in order for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, it would be enough to exercise the vote and in the most direct way possible.
We know, since Napoleon "the Little One", that it was something thought.
Universal suffrage, although a necessary condition for democracy, is not enough on its own and can even become an “instrument of oppression,” as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, Lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum had, in this respect, a double revealing effect: it showed the need for a powerful return from the political sphere, but also the worrying feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruence.
You need to think about this ambivalence in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have now shifted and, in many cases, Republican soldiers are no longer moving in the right direction.
We will not win if we demand a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and in a disorderly manner.
A blank signature to the absolute European monarch or a gap in the nationalist hole: what options for the citizen!
No, we do not want to take a coup d'état, but a common, full-fledged, peaceful and continuous exercise of options and democracy, this time on a European scale.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we would not know where to end the list), because there is only one crisis, the crisis of Europe.
The whole of Europe is the one that follows the orders of the markets and the rating agencies, the one that suffers from their impotence and their lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that suffers humiliation in the international sphere.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is the whole of Europe that slowly loses sovereignty and, with it, each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is that popular sovereignty recovers the helm of the European project.
Because only together will Europeans be able to reduce the weight of their debts, free themselves from the markets and prepare their future through investment.
The exit from the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be made without full democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead us to disaster.
Having fought for a long time against this proposal of the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic governance.
Let it be.
But to think of it without greater political and democratic integration, and without it being lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and would lead us to a new dead end.
We must take on a new stage of European construction.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" Republicans.
The interest-motivated revolution would not be enough.
This lesson is still applicable.
We must build a more integrated Europe from an economic point of view.
It can only be achieved by building a more democratic Europe at the political level, a true European popular sovereignty.
To build Europe, let us make Europeans.
Cards with "contactless" chip are generalized
The World Chip Card Show starts on Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, with an optimistic atmosphere.
In fact, 2011 should end with an 11% increase in global microprocessor card sales (bank cards, SIM-card phones, etc.), with a total of 6 billion units, according to Eurosmart’s calculations.
The most powerful segment is that of contactless technology, which allows you to pay for public transportation or purchases simply by bringing the card closer to a reader.
This year 460 million contactless chip cards will be sold worldwide, 320 million more than the previous year!
Its share is expected to continue to increase in 2012 (580 million units expected) and account for about 10% of the global chip card market (6,925 million cards).
Europe, which has long been lagging behind with regard to the Asia-Pacific region, is gaining ground in the contactless payment sector.
Around 26 million Visa bank cards already have this feature, which is accepted at 75,000 payment terminals.
In France, its beginnings are more modest: 400,000 contactless Visa cards are being used.
But the large surfaces work for four.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million contactless Pass MasterCard cards this year.
To make the upper gear, however, it is necessary for banks to make them available to their customers.
“There are two major French establishments that have committed to systematically disseminate in the future, among their customers, bank cards equipped with the contactless system,” says Gérard Nébouy, CEO of Visa Europe France.
Banks try to pay by mobile phone
But it is only a first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
Currently, there are few devices equipped with NFC (Near Field Communication) technology, which is essential for making transactions.
"They're backing out."
“But I should finally experience a real boom next year.”
“We expect between 80 and 120 million units to be sold in 2012 worldwide,” explains Marc Bertin, President of Eurosmart.
But the banks take the lead.
Crédit agricole bank announced yesterday the launch of a test between December and next June in Caen.
iPhones will be matched by around 200 customers and collaborators with a case that allows contactless payment.
The BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the Société générale has also stated yesterday that it is preparing to market an offer that allows its customers to pay without contact via their mobile.
From the Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris is concerned about the links between Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The links between the Al Qaeda terrorist group in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian Boko Haram sect, which has long been suspected, have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algeria's Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel even claimed that Algiers already "has the certainty".
“The way both organizations operate and intelligence reports show they’re cooperating,” he explained, without providing further details.
Paris seems to come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two French nationals in Niger last January is said to have resumed.
Kidnapped in a restaurant in Niamey by people related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the next day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by French special forces.
In the debris of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators discovered several telephone chips belonging to the terrorists.
Aye terrorist
The study of the calls made indicates several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers especially captured the interest of researchers: one leads to a Nigerian who has long remained in Maiduguri, a northern Nigerian city, the birthplace of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who is supposedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
"This is progress, but we must certainly expect to have more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram."
"But it's possible."
“We have known for years that the sect enjoys external financial and intellectual support and is increasingly active,” said Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, such "supports" had become increasingly evident in the evolution and speeches of Boko Haram or in its operating modes, which now involve the use of increasingly complex and similar Kamikazes or explosive devices as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has since been pressing Abuya to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities, in fact, have long regarded the group as a community of illuminators not worthy of interest.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (meaning, in Hausa, "Western education is a sin"), prompts the establishment of an Islamic emirate in northern Nigeria.
In this poor region, the partnership is experiencing rapid success.
It politicizes and demands strict respect from the sharia, while its militants launch themselves into the fight against the wicked central government.
The latter are primarily oriented to churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were especially active and the attacks against the police stations multiplied.
Abuya’s reaction was, as usual, widespread.
The army attacked the city and recorded 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested alive, receives death in prison.
Since then, the sect has radicalized and abandoned its northern fiefdoms.
Last Christmas, he claims an attack that killed 80 people in Jos and then another in Abuya.
In June, Boko Haram again attacked Abuya, in particular the police-protected headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of its kind.
In August, the United Nations local headquarters became its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which would span from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria, worries all security experts.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and the Somalis of Al-Chebab operate in Kenya, Boko Haram emerges as a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned him against Boko Haram and said he was willing to "share all the information".
