The Nord Stream, a new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which directly communicates Western Europe with Russia passing through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, has wanted to celebrate the event with a big pump.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated on the Baltic coast, between orchestral music and a delicate buffet, at the opening of the Nord Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned together the valve steering wheel that controls Russian gas entry into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will reach Western Europe each year through a first 1,224-km-long tunnel connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Mecklenburg-Pomerania Land.
A second pipeline should be completed by the end of 2012 that will provide a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, that is, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube along the same path.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this enormous work presents areas of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow the supply of gas directly to Germany, avoiding the ground passage by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Strikingly, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to close its access to the markets of Western Europe.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe’s energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in making its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically unites us,” said Fillon during the pipeline’s inauguration, demonstrating to what extent major gas sector contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom’s executives, numerous in Lubmin, at the gas arrival point.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from World War II.
“It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, by precaution,” said Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to extend measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in its entire length: either by valves, or by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Sweden’s waters, but the project officials gave up on it when they saw that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to permanently establish itself at sea off its shores.
"In case of failure, we will interrupt the passage of the gas in less than a minute," says Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller.
In case of leakage, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, as they have planned joints that, according to forecasts, will have a leak every 100,000 years.
Control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by an underwater robot, carried out by a ship, carrying out external inspections, as well as by a device circulating inside the pipeline.
In the form of a pure, it is introduced into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible deformations of the metal.
The gas pipeline has been designed to run for fifty years without the need for any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is guaranteed simply by the pressure.
At the beginning it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by the German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, Nord Stream, in charge of building and exploiting the pipeline.
It is based in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is especially favorable.
After that, Gazprom leased to that company, for a renewable period of twenty-five years, all of the gas transportation capacities.
“Gazprom will pay you for the total capacity, regardless of how much gas is actually transported,” says Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline has been carried out by 30% with the contribution of the shareholders and by 70% by means of bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom alone assumes the risk of spending.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy pine-planted coast.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet gate.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas upon arrival, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
The total capacity will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand booklet.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people back the taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine booklet is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aging over time.
However, the Moleskine booklets with the current look were born... in 1997.
The Milan-based Italian company Modo Modo decided at that time to launch a design notebook, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, was responsible for the launch of the new product.
The booklet is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin (top skin), which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the banquets.
This type of booklet was highly valued by writers and travelers.
“Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of the avant-garde artists until the 20th century,” says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Mode Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the early years, in which only 3,000 booklets were designed, has remained far behind.
Moleskine goes beyond Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer’s profile, since the notebook attracts both business men and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cult.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers in its beginnings, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its books in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the city centre, and has been able to impose its identity.
“We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural firm goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also released a booklet with leopard caps, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agendas, pens, computer cases... The brand encompasses a wide range of supports.
A success that provokes envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, currently Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for the Employment of Persons with Disabilities begins today.
Despite a resolute public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among people with disabilities doubles the average rate: 19%, compared with 9% for the entire population.
Disadvantage?
“No,” said Eric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
“The progress made in the last 15 years is considerable.
“At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
“But there’s still a lot to do.”
It should be noted that disabled people continue to face numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They usually have a more advanced age: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not completed the bachelor’s degree and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
That is, there are numerous issues that make it especially difficult to return to the world of work and that "constitute the solution to the problem," says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those that are not mentioned; the mentality of the people progresses, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Enterprise association for the Cité noted that the directors surveyed have "a level of knowledge about low disabilities", with an "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physical or intellectual disabilities".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, a goal set in a 1987 law.
According to the latest figures available, as of 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
“We now reach around 3%,” said Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The test: the number of establishments "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, has decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has generated great pressure for companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects true awareness, particularly among the large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies with between 20 and 49 employees have employees with disabilities in their workforce, compared with 82% of companies with between 100 and 199 employees.
